<dl id="n57075c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n57" href="#n57075c">N57 (VI.B.47)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n57all.htm#n57075c"> 75(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Tiresias B / m <font color="green">[eyes]</font> / &mdash; W / <font color="green">[[??]</font> <font color="green">[??]</font>] / bi = M</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Der verwundet hat, wird auch heilen&rdquo;, hei&szlig;t ein Orakelwort des griechischen Mythos, der vom Seher Teiresias handelt, wie er verflucht ward, Weib zu sein, dann aber wieder in einen Mann zur&uuml;ckverwandelt wurde. <br><font color="green">[&ldquo;He who has wounded will also heal,&rdquo; is an oracle from Greek myth about the seer <mark>Tiresias</mark>: how he was cursed to become a woman, but was then turned back again into a man.]</font> <small> Heinrich Zimmer, <a name="HZMI2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HZMI2"><cite title="source">Maya der indische Mythos</cite></a> (1936) 18</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
